{{nn|bio|date=December 2013}}
'''Austin Cowles''' (May 3, 1792 <U+2013> January 15, 1872) was a leader in the early [[Latter Day Saint movement]], serving on the [[High council (Latter Day Saints)|high council]] in [[Nauvoo, Illinois]].<ref> http://www.strangite.org/Famous.htm {{rs|date=October 2013}}</ref> Cowles was later a counselor to Nauvoo [[stake president]] [[William Marks (Latter Day Saints)|William Marks]].  

==Early role in Latter-day Saint moment==
Cowles was baptized into the Latter Day Saint movement's [[Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)|Church of Christ]] in 1832 in [[New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://josephsmithpapers.org/person/austin-cowles |title=Cowles, Austin - Details |publisher=Josephsmithpapers.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>   

He moved to Nauvoo in 1840, and was appointed to the Nauvoo high council on February 6, 1841; he was appointed counselor to Marks in March 1841.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://josephsmithpapers.org/person/austin-cowles |title=Cowles, Austin - Details |publisher=Josephsmithpapers.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>

==Dissent in Nauvoo==
On June 1, 1843, Cowles's daughter Elvira married [[Joseph Smith]] as a [[plural marriage|plural wife]].<ref> http://www.josephsmithspolygamy.com/JSPolyandry/9PolyandryAccusations/ElviraCowles.html {{rs|date=October 2013}}</ref> Six month earlier, on December 1, 1842, Elvira had married Johnathan Holmes.<ref> http://www.wivesofjosephsmith.org/28-ElviraCowlesHolmes.htm {{rs|date=October 2013}}</ref>

On September 12, 1843, Cowles resigned his seat in the high council. Afterwards, Cowles was "was far more outspoken and energetic in his opposition to polygamy than almost any other man in Nauvoo." Afterwards, he "was looked upon as a seceder."<ref> http://www.exmormon.org/mormon/mormon010.htm {{rs|date=October 2013}}</ref><ref> http://mormon-church-history.blogspot.com/2011/03/mormon-history-sep-21-1843.html {{rs|date=October 2013}} </ref>

On April 18, 1844, [[First Presidency]] member [[William Law (Latter Day Saints)|William Law]] and his wife Jane were excommunicated from the church,<ref> Cook, Lyndon W. "William Law, Nauvoo Dissenter". (10.2 MB) [[BYU Studies]]. Winter, 1982. Vol. 22, no. 1, p. 47-72</ref> along with his brother [[Wilson Law]], a brigadier general in the [[Nauvoo Legion]]. Also cut off were [[Robert D. Foster]] and Howard Smith.

On May 18, Cowles was excommunicated for apostasy, along with James Blakesley, [[Francis M. Higbee]] of the Nauvoo Legion, and [[Charles Ivins]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://byustudies.byu.edu/hc/6/20.html |title=Chapter 19 : Charges against President Smith before the Circuit Court - His Voluntary Appearances at Court - Treatment - Return to Nauvoo |publisher=Byustudies.byu.edu |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref> On May 29, the high council published document purporting to show Higbee's brother [[Chauncey L. Higbee]] had also committed misdeeds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boap.org/LDS/Nauvoo-Neighbor/1844/5-29-1844.pdf |title=Nauvoo Neighbor |publisher=Boap.org |accessdate=2013-10-05}}</ref>

==''Nauvoo Expositor''==
In 1844, Cowles swore an affidavit accusing the church of teaching the doctrine of plural marriage. This statement was published along with others, in the first and only issue of the ''[[Nauvoo Expositor]]''. After the publication, Joseph Smith ordered the press destroyed, ultimately resulting in [[Death of Joseph Smith|his arrest and death]].

==Strangite==
After Smith's death, Cowles accepted the succession claims of [[James Strang]]. In 1847, Cowles was appointed by Strang to be the presiding [[high priest (Latter Day Saints)|high priest]] in [[Kirtland, Ohio]].

